Low-blast, read-only reverse engineering. I’ll inspect the specified supervision files and runtime config flags first, then answer only from cited code evidence.
The first pass shows `mk-spec-memory` has explicit daemon re-election code, while `mk-code-index` records the child as owner and exits with it. I’m reading the remaining supervision tail plus the bridge/socket code now because stale-socket respawn is delegated through `launcher-ipc-bridge.cjs`, not only the launchers.
The current code splits “relaunch decision” into two layers: shared `superviseChildExit()` schedules relaunch unless the exit is intentional or crash-loop give-up, while `mk-spec-memory` adds a backoff-time abort when its owning runtime is gone. I’m checking the daemon-side socket binding next so the lifecycle trace can include bind/unbind rather than stopping at the launcher.
The runtime configs only carry a note for re-election now; the actual default is in `mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs`. The ENV reference confirms the configs “no longer set it,” so I’ll treat launcher code as the source of truth for gating/defaults.
Daemon-side socket bind/unbind is in `startIpcSocketServer()`: it reclaims only a UID-owned socket node on `EADDRINUSE`, and unlinks on close. That means stale socket files are not proactively swept at launcher startup; they are reclaimed when the daemon attempts to bind or when a secondary deep-probe decides to respawn.
The “dead socket” recovery is reactive, not a background supervisor. If no runtime or non-warm CLI starts the corresponding launcher, there is no process left to run the respawn path.
Clean daemon shutdowns do call `ipcBridge.close()` and should unlink the socket. A stale socket with no listener therefore points to unclean death, failed cleanup, or a path whose listener died without reaching that close handler.
`mk-code-index` can legitimately show multiple launcher processes because each extra session enters the live-owner branch and runs a per-session reconnecting proxy. That differs from “three owners”; owner lease points at the child, while bridge launchers remain as client proxies.
One caveat for daemon internals: the launchers execute built `dist/*.js`; I’ve cited TS source for readability. I’m checking the compiled entrypoints for the same lifecycle hooks so the final can distinguish source evidence from runtime-entry evidence.
## IT2 — live supervision code trace
### Lifecycle trace (functions + flow)
- Runtime startup: the three runtimes spawn the per-daemon launchers directly. OpenCode runs `mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs`, `mk-skill-advisor-launcher.cjs`, and `mk-code-index-launcher.cjs` from `opencode.json:18-23`, `opencode.json:47-52`, and `opencode.json:68-73`. Claude and Codex mirror those launcher commands in `.claude/mcp.json:9-13`, `.claude/mcp.json:37-41`, `.claude/mcp.json:57-61`, `.codex/config.toml:60-63`, `.codex/config.toml:86-88`, and `.codex/config.toml:102-104`.
- Owner lease acquisition: each launcher has `acquireOwnerLeaseFile()` and `classifyOwnerLease()`. `mk-spec-memory` classifies an existing owner as `live-owner`, `unknown-eperm`, `stale-pid`, `ppid-1-orphan`, or `stale-heartbeat-reclaim` using `processLiveness()` and parent-pid/heartbeat checks at `.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:433-490`. Skill-advisor and code-index have the same pattern at `.opencode/bin/mk-skill-advisor-launcher.cjs:457-513` and `.opencode/bin/mk-code-index-launcher.cjs:427-486`.
- Secondary session path: if an owner lease is live, launchers call `bridgeOrReportLeaseHeld()` instead of starting another owner. The shared bridge prefers the owner-recorded `socketPath`, deep-probes with JSON-RPC `initialize`, and returns `action: 'bridge'` when alive or `action: 'respawn'` after repeated failures at `.opencode/bin/lib/launcher-ipc-bridge.cjs:387-436`.
- Child daemon spawn: `mk-spec-memory` `launchServer()` spawns `context-server.js` with `SPECKIT_BACKEND_ONLY=1`, writes a lease including `childPid`, starts the RSS watchdog, and, when re-election is enabled, uses detached stdio and `childProcess.unref()` at `.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:1299-1335`.
- Child daemon spawn: `mk-skill-advisor` `launchServer()` spawns `advisor-server.js`, writes the launcher lease with child pid, and exits when that child exits at `.opencode/bin/mk-skill-advisor-launcher.cjs:1144-1182`.
- Child daemon spawn: `mk-code-index` `launchServer()` spawns `index.js`, then refreshes the owner lease from the launcher pid to the child pid at `.opencode/bin/mk-code-index-launcher.cjs:863-890`.
- Socket bind: the daemon children call `startIpcSocketServer()`. Runtime dist confirms `context-server.js` binds at `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/dist/context-server.js:1920-1929`, advisor binds at `.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/dist/mcp_server/advisor-server.js:241`, and code-index binds at `.opencode/skills/system-code-graph/mcp_server/dist/index.js:127-130`.
- Socket bind details: `startIpcSocketServer()` creates the socket dir, checks ownership/mode, refuses symlink bind targets, calls `server.listen(socketPath)`, and on `EADDRINUSE` unlinks only a provably safe stale Unix socket before retrying at `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/shared/dist/ipc/socket-server.js:208-335`.
- Socket unbind: clean shutdown closes active sockets/server and unlinks the Unix socket in the returned handle’s `close()` at `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/shared/dist/ipc/socket-server.js:356-379`. Runtime daemons call this close from shutdown: context at `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/dist/context-server.js:1282-1335`, advisor at `.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/dist/mcp_server/advisor-server.js:113-138`, and code-index at `.opencode/skills/system-code-graph/mcp_server/dist/index.js:78-98`.
- Signal/shutdown: `mk-spec-memory` routes `SIGINT`, `SIGTERM`, `SIGHUP`, and `SIGQUIT` through `shutdownLauncherForSignal()` at `.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:1440-1518`. Skill-advisor and code-index have simpler signal handlers that kill the child and exit at `.opencode/bin/mk-skill-advisor-launcher.cjs:1185-1208` and `.opencode/bin/mk-code-index-launcher.cjs:911-928`.

### Relaunch decision (exact predicate)
- The shared relaunch-vs-exit decision is `superviseChildExit(event, actions)` in `.opencode/bin/lib/model-server-supervision.cjs:251-272`.
- Exact effective predicate: relaunch happens only when `event.intentional` is false and `decision.giveUp` is false. `decision.giveUp` comes from `createCrashLoopGuard().recordDeath()`, where `giveUp: deathsInWindow >= maxDeaths` at `.opencode/bin/lib/model-server-supervision.cjs:224-232`.
- The code path is: `if (event.intentional) { clearLease(); exit(...) }`; else record death; `if (decision.giveUp) { clearLease(); reapProcessGroup(...); mirrorSignal(...) or exit(...) }`; else `actions.scheduleRelaunch(decision.backoffMs)` at `.opencode/bin/lib/model-server-supervision.cjs:251-271`.
- `mk-spec-memory` adds a second guard when the scheduled relaunch timer fires. Exact abort predicate: `Boolean(shuttingDown) || currentPpid !== initialPpid || currentPpid === 1` in `shouldAbortRelaunchOnFire()` at `.opencode/bin/lib/model-server-supervision.cjs:319-321`, used by `mk-spec-memory` before calling `launchServer()` at `.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:1353-1368`.
- Advisor and code-index do not use this shared relaunch predicate for their main MCP child. Advisor child exit clears leases and exits at `.opencode/bin/mk-skill-advisor-launcher.cjs:1156-1167`; code-index child exit clears leases and exits at `.opencode/bin/mk-code-index-launcher.cjs:893-902`.

### Stale-socket handling (reap? block-on-exists?)
- Daemon IPC sockets are reclaimed on bind, not proactively at launcher startup. On `EADDRINUSE`, `startIpcSocketServer()` calls `canUnlinkExistingSocket()`, unlinks the socket only if it is a same-UID socket under an allowed root, then retries `listenOnce()` at `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/shared/dist/ipc/socket-server.js:320-335`.
- Mere path existence does not block startup if the node is a reclaimable same-user socket. It does block/fail closed if the path is a symlink, non-socket, foreign-owned, outside allowed roots, or otherwise fails the safety fence at `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/shared/dist/ipc/socket-server.js:102-140` and `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/shared/dist/ipc/socket-server.js:218-253`.
- Failed connect does not directly unlink. `probeDaemon()` reports `status: 'dead'` on socket errors/timeouts at `.opencode/bin/lib/launcher-ipc-bridge.cjs:145-230`; `probeLeaseHolderWithRetries()` requires repeated dead probes at `.opencode/bin/lib/launcher-ipc-bridge.cjs:332-358`; then `maybeBridgeLeaseHolder()` returns `{ action: 'respawn' }` at `.opencode/bin/lib/launcher-ipc-bridge.cjs:421-423`.
- Respawn after dead daemon socket is launcher-specific and reactive. Spec-memory requires both an owner pid and `childPid`; missing `childPid` makes respawn inert at `.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:774-793`. Skill-advisor resolves a target pid and respawns inside `respawnAfterDeadSocket()` at `.opencode/bin/mk-skill-advisor-launcher.cjs:616-683`. Code-index respawns through `respawnAfterDeadSocket()` only when a `respawnChildPid` is available at `.opencode/bin/mk-code-index-launcher.cjs:639-682`.
- The HF model-server socket has separate stale handling in `model-server-supervision.cjs`: existing socket is probed, a respawn lock is acquired, a recorded model-server pid is reaped if needed, and `unlinkModelServerSocket()` runs before listening at `.opencode/bin/lib/model-server-supervision.cjs:1159-1211`. Its `EADDRINUSE` handler also refuses to reclaim if a recorded live resident exists at `.opencode/bin/lib/model-server-supervision.cjs:1279-1297`.
- If a daemon fully dies and leaves `/tmp/<service>/daemon-ipc.sock`, nothing reclaims it until another launcher or daemon bind path runs. Warm-only CLI probes explicitly do not cold-spawn; the README says `--warm-only` exits `75` instead of cold-spawning at `.opencode/bin/README.md:161-164`.

### Launcher divergence (why advisor/spec-memory dead, code-index x3)
- The observed state is confirmed in the diagnosis: skill-advisor and spec-memory are down with stale sockets, while code-index has three launchers alive and a working warm probe at `.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/007-mcp-daemon-reliability/031-daemon-flap-root-cause-research/research/live-diagnosis.md:5-10`.
- The README states the lifecycle divergence directly: `mk-spec-memory` is the hardened reference for persistent logging, detached daemon re-election/adoption, and owner-release-on-shutdown; `mk-code-index` and `mk-skill-advisor` “currently stop with their child and rely on fresh-session reload plus bridge/respawn paths instead” at `.opencode/bin/README.md:93`.
- Spec-memory can relaunch its main child while the launcher is still alive: child exit calls `superviseChildExit()` and schedules `launchServer()` after backoff at `.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:1337-1376`. But on owner shutdown with re-election enabled, `shutdownLauncherForSignal()` exits the launcher and leaves only the detached context-server daemon at `.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:1449-1471`. If that detached daemon later dies, no launcher remains to respawn it.
- Skill-advisor has no re-election branch and no main-child relaunch. Its child exit path calls `shutdownModelServerForLauncherExit()`, clears leases, and exits/mirrors signal at `.opencode/bin/mk-skill-advisor-launcher.cjs:1156-1172`; its signal handler kills the child and exits at `.opencode/bin/mk-skill-advisor-launcher.cjs:1185-1200`.
- Code-index also exits with its child, but multiple live launcher processes are expected under multiple live sessions because a secondary session in `launcherMain()` detects the live owner and bridges its stdio to the owner socket at `.opencode/bin/mk-code-index-launcher.cjs:953-970`. The session proxy attaches to the daemon socket and keeps event-loop resources active after `start()` wires stdin/stdout/socket listeners at `.opencode/bin/lib/launcher-session-proxy.cjs:814-837`.
- My read: code-index `x3` is more likely “three session/proxy launcher processes” than “three daemon owners.” I cannot prove that without inspecting the live process tree/socket clients; the code path supports it.

### Re-election reality (resurrect vs adopt-only; gating flag + default)
- Re-election is wired only in `mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs`: `daemonReelectionEnabled()`, `contextServerSpawnIo()`, and `shouldReleaseDaemonForReelection()` at `.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:196-215`.
- The current default is code-owned, not config-owned. `daemonReelectionEnabled()` returns true unless `SPECKIT_DAEMON_REELECTION` is exactly `0` or `off` at `.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:205-207`. `ENV_REFERENCE.md` confirms default `on`, says runtime configs no longer set it, and identifies launcher code as the source of truth at `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/ENV_REFERENCE.md:179`.
- The runtime configs contain a `_NOTE_DAEMON_REELECTION` note but do not set `SPECKIT_DAEMON_REELECTION=1`: `opencode.json:43`, `.claude/mcp.json:33`, and `.codex/config.toml:83`.
- Re-election release is gated by `shouldReleaseDaemonForReelection({ enabled: daemonReelectionEnabled(), hasLiveDaemon: isChildRunning(childProcess) })` at `.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:1453`. On true, it kills/reaps the non-adoptable HF model-server if present, removes the process `exit` lease cleanup, clears only the owner lease, and exits without killing context-server at `.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:1449-1471`.
- It is not an autonomous resurrection supervisor. It can adopt an already-running released daemon when a fresh launcher sees a stale launcher lease with live `childPid` and bridgeable socket at `.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:1570-1587`.
- It can also respawn a dead/unbridgeable daemon, but only reactively when a new launcher starts and reaches the stale-lease path. That path takes the respawn lock, reaps the recorded `childPid` if needed, and then launches a replacement at `.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:1589-1649`.
- If there is no live owner and no new non-warm launcher invocation, fully-dead spec-memory is not resurrected. Warm-only probes will keep reporting down instead of cold-spawning per `.opencode/bin/README.md:161-164`.

### Cross-session lease interaction (kill-what-another-needs?)
- Strict owner lease is intended to prevent duplicate owners: a second launcher detecting a live owner bridges instead of spawning. That is the live-owner path in spec-memory at `.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:1556-1568`, skill-advisor at `.opencode/bin/mk-skill-advisor-launcher.cjs:716-730`, and code-index at `.opencode/bin/mk-code-index-launcher.cjs:953-970`.
- Yes, one session’s exit can kill a daemon another session still needs for skill-advisor and code-index. Their owner launcher signal handlers kill the child and exit without checking active secondary IPC clients: `.opencode/bin/mk-skill-advisor-launcher.cjs:1185-1200` and `.opencode/bin/mk-code-index-launcher.cjs:911-928`.
- Spec-memory default-on re-election is the exception: owner shutdown releases the context-server instead of killing it at `.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:1449-1471`. If `SPECKIT_DAEMON_REELECTION=0/off`, the old kill path runs and can kill a daemon used by bridged secondaries at `.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:1474-1506`.
- The dead-owner-pid/live-childPid bug is explicitly addressed in current spec-memory stale reclaim: `leaseHeldFromFile()` keys stale detection on the launcher pid at `.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:565-581`, then the stale path reads `staleLease.childPid`, adopts if live and bridgeable, or serializes reap+respawn otherwise at `.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:1570-1615`.
- One adjacent cross-session risk remains visible in code: spec-memory’s re-election release kills the HF model-server sidecar as “non-adoptable” at `.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:1454-1464`. The runtime configs intentionally share that HF socket between spec-memory and skill-advisor at `opencode.json:40` and `opencode.json:65`, so embedding consumers may see a sidecar recycle even when context-server itself is released.

